Turkey expands its diplomatic horizon
Long before Turkey sought to join the European Union, the European powers were interested in penetrating deep into Turkey's interior.
On the eastern side of the Bosporus, perhaps just 20 steps into Asia, stands one of the finest relics of this failed imperial endeavor.
Hydarpasha railway station was designed by the two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in the Neo-Renaissance style.
At least that's what the guides tell you.
The building sits riding on the end of the railway ladder with a tower at each corner of the front and thus looks like some provincial German town hall.
The rock is dirty.
The whole building is about to fall apart.
But once you're inside the vaulted ticket counter, there's no doubt about the grandeur of the project, whose westernest access was this.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Baghdad Society.
Germany, a late bloomer in the imperialist game, had to realize its ambitions of dominating the Middle East by means of a train link to Damascus, Baghdad, and beyond to what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany's imperialist plans were crippled during World War I.
His railroads were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arabs.
The relative isolation from its surrounding region, created by the insurmountable limits of the Cold War, has disappeared.
British forces withdrew from Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria
And there was also bad news for Hyderpasha Station.
In 1917, a train of ammunition flew into the air, destroying the artistic roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has been slowly falling apart, largely out of the picture.
Today, however, this railway line serves, at least symbolically, as a gateway to Anatolia and all of its eastern regions, to highlight the expansion of Turkey's diplomatic horizon.
The ruling Justice and Development Party, the AKP, has introduced a new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the neighbouring regions created by the borders of the Cold War has disappeared.
Now there is a policy of approximation.
It is remarkable that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iran and Iraq and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
In order to assess the key facts of this new foreign policy, I took the night train to Ankara, Turkey, to visit one of the leading experts on foreign policy of the AKP, the Turkish Member of Parliament Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning, about ten and a half hours later, after a bumpy ride on the tracks that produced the ancient world's equivalency in the famous documentary "The Night Mail", I arrived in the Turkish capital, which is considered a new city for the new secular state project to turn its back on the Ottoman past.
The AKP, however, known for its Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in Turkish unity
This has caused a lot of mistrust in the West, especially in Washington.
A taxi took me to the AKP headquarters, a specially designed, state-of-the-art stone and steel building in a developing suburb surrounded by semi-finished shopping malls and pubs where middle managers in suits, both men and women, met to close the first business of the day.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician from almost any other political party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he even packed a blackberry.
"The objective of the Party's foreign policy is now to integrate Turkey with its immediate neighbours.
The Cold War was an exception", he tells me.
Turkey had been cut off from its hinterland.
Nowadays, she has to look east and west at the same time.
There's no one or the other.
She'd have to do both.
"But surely Turkey could at some point", I asked, "be forced to decide?"
"Turkey", he said, "did not want to have to face this decision".
He then pointed out a point that almost everyone I spoke to here has said almost routinely: Turkey's relations, not only with the Middle East but also with the Caucasus and the Black Sea, are just as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be that Europe as a whole can, in a broad sense, travel eastwards on the same railways as Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha railway station, after another largely sleepless night, I thought of these two German gentlemen, Mr. Knight and Mr. Conu, who had watched the construction of this building 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to learn that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East could now, for the most part, be in the hands of Turkey.
And as I waited at the docks for the ferry to take me back across the Bosporus, I remembered that in those days Turkey was always called "the sick man of Europe".
At least at the time, there seemed little doubt as to which continent should claim this fascinating land.
In memory of Vernon Handley and William Woodruff.
Mark Brown writes: As Guildford's musical director since 1962, Vernon "Tod" Handley (call on September 11) was responsible for the Guildford Philharmonic and Choir.
As part of his music program for the city, he founded his great youth choir, Proteus, the following year.
It was designed for youths up to the age of 21, but when the choir last sang in 1979, some of us were in our late 20's - we simply refused to leave the choir.
The name "Proteus" (the mythological shape-shifter) stood for the willingness and ability of the choir, any piece of music presented to it, whether it was a madrigal or from the Messiah, whether a capella or with a full orchestra.
The musical versatility of such a young choir was often astonishing, always exciting, and was solely due to the inspiration of that man and his enthusiasm for music, which never waned over the years.
How often did death stop us from "leting the music speak for itself"?
He used to say, "The composer knows what he wants".
It's all in the music.
So sing it!"
His conducting style was absolutely clear and precise, never dominating, but never exaggerating.
No matter how high the musical level was, he always demanded something even higher.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If any conductor should have been knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well during the last two decades, from 1962 to 1982, when he led the Guildford Philharmonic.
Over the past 40 years or so, I've written reviews for over a hundred of his concerts, and I can honestly say that I've never been disappointed by one - often I've been inspired by them.
Death Handley was that rare combination of greatness and personal humility.
He hated conductors who, he said, simply "went around the world with one or two famous show pets".
So many of us will miss him.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
In your letter of inquiry to William Woodruff (September 25), you write that "he resumed teaching economic history at Oxford in 1946 and received a Houblon-Norman research fellowship in 1950 ... while simultaneously studying for a BSc, MA and PhD.
