`Auto-bee', which avoids collisions
To advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan was inspired by nature, more specifically, by bees.
The Japanese company has developed a robot that relies on the swarm behavior of bees to avoid accidents.
This robot is a bio-mimetic car robot drive or BR23C and represents the first step in accident prevention technologies.
The engineers at the Nissan Motor Co. Technical Development Center have developed this small robot in cooperation with the Research Center for Advanced Science and Technology at the renowned University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Head of Technology PR and R&D Brand Management, the BR23C is an extension of the Nissan four-layer safety shield.
This robot is supposed to make sure that the cars of this brand are able to avoid collisions.
During flight, each bee builds its own oval-shaped airspace, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important feature is the bee's faceted eyes, which can see in all directions at an angle of 300 degrees, allowing it to fly uninterrupted in its personal airspace.
To replicate the round-the-clock perspective, the engineers developed what they called the Laser Range Finder (LRF).
It detects obstacles up to two metres away from the BR23C and within a 180-degree radius, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor that is immediately translated into a collision avoidance signal
`The moment an obstacle is detected, the little robot will mimic the flight of the bee and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at an angle of 90o or greater to avoid collision.
The biggest difference from any other system is that this maneuver of evasion is absolutely instinctive.
If it were not, the robot would not be able to react at sufficient speed to avoid obstacles,' explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike a bee, the robot can neither move up or down, nor overhead; it can only move in two dimensions and in a direction that allows it to rotate its wheels and not in the infinite directions and infinite ways, as the bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used the rotation function in addition to acceleration and braking functions to help the small robot avoid collisions.
`This device only needs a few seconds to process the information and act on it.
It does not require the information or the intuitive logic of the maneuvers performed to be stored, so it can work continuously with only a few dozen KB of storage space.
That sounds surprising, but it's not about the GBs or even the MBs of the storage.
This is the first step in the development of technologies for immediate collision prevention, a technology that Nissan predicts will be introduced to production cars in the next decade.
The robot works with lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than a variety of lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible use of this technology in the future could be the integration of the unit with a GPS navigation system via satellite to guide you to your destination while avoiding obstacles along the way.
