Fox in the chicken coop
Because of a person's drug use, life and health insurance companies in America often refuse to sign a contract with a customer.
Data protection experts fear that the data market could become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programmes that link the use of the medicinal data to the consent of the person concerned.
These should be in independent hands, or else we'll give the fox the chickens", Richard Dick, the developer of the prescription tracking program, quotes the Washington Post.
Insurance establishes the fees and amounts to be paid in the event of damage depending on the health of the customer and, should the risk be overestimated, the insurance is not completed.
In the past, the client was sent for a medical examination and the contract was concluded only with knowledge of the results.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper method: using the customer's ID number, he gets the last one and a half years of pharmacy data, which is, what drugs were purchased, and the program calculates the patient's illness and health status.
For example, if he regularly buys large amounts of cholesterol-lowering drugs, it would suggest that his blood fat levels are untreatably high, which would automatically put him in a higher-risk group.
There are several versions of the programme in circulation - some even define a risk multiplier, so that the insurers only have to handle the paperwork more, but there are minor difficulties.
One of the disadvantages is that many medications can be taken for different purposes, like migraines and heat waves, but also for depression.
The latter is a high risk factor from the insurers' point of view, while the ones mentioned above are not.
For the purposes of data collection and processing, companies have been set up that ask the patient for their consent before they obtain the data.
They must now do so by law, although there have been no penalties for omissions.
Some companies even process the results of laboratory tests and combine them with the data on drug use to provide an even more accurate picture of patients' health.
More and more companies have access to data, and at the same time, controlling their use is becoming more difficult.
Although there is a separate data protection law for health data, its effect is limited to healthcare and insurance service providers.
The bill has already been introduced to Congress, which would allow the authorities to control data processing companies.
Dick Richard sees that this is not enough, so he wants to develop his programme so that the data can only be passed on with the consent of the data subject.
Another question, of course, is that the data subject can hardly deny access to his data, since the insurance companies do not otherwise enter into a contract with him.
And so the chickens are somehow left to the fox's mercy.
